<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Hachette's Memories Magazine to Fade
   Next Month, but TV Spinoff Will Live On
   ----
   By Patrick M. Reilly
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   F.HAC GE
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Remember Memories? It's history.
   After months of trying to sell the nostalgia news
magazine, Diamandis Communications Inc., a unit of French
publisher Hachette S.A., said it will cease regular
publication with the October issue of Memories.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The announcement follows weeks of last-ditch efforts to
save the magazine, and a decision by Mortimer Zuckerman,
chairman of U.S. News &amp; World Report and The Atlantic
magazines, to withdraw from negotiations to buy Memories. Mr.
Zuckerman cited a dismal forecast for magazine advertising,
and Hachette said it decided not to wait for other bidders to
emerge.
   Didier Guerin, president of the U.S. unit of Hachette,
blamed Memories's demise on a weak economy and reduced
advertising budgets. "It became clear the potential
profitability of Memories was being pushed years down the
road," he said. "We weren't prepared to suffer all those
losses."
   Mr. Guerin said closing Memories will slightly ease
Hachette's debt burden from its $712 million purchase of
Diamandis. "Not carrying Memories slightly improves the cash
flow," he said. In May, Hachette put Woman's Day magazine up
for sale to relieve debt. Bidders fell short of the estimated
$175 million to $200 million that Hachette sought, and the
women's magazine was pulled off the market.
   Peter Diamandis, president of DCI and founder of Memories,
said the magazine will publish two special issues each year
and that the magazine could be brought back to life "should
the advertising climate improve." Plans for a syndicated TV
show based on Memories are unaffected, DCI executives said.
The first installment of the half-hour news-nostalgia show is
scheduled to air Sept. 15 on NBC. An NBC spokeswoman said the
network is still "excited" about the weekly show.
   The closure of Memories indicates that even seemingly
thriving magazines are at risk in the current bleak
advertising climate. Memories was named "Best New Magazine"
in 1989 by Advertising Age. A little more than two years old,
it grew to an 800,000 circulation rate base, and its ad pages
were expected to double to 325 in 1990. Its last issue, in
October, was to be its first as a monthly; it had been
published bimonthly.
   "We are very disappointed," said Gregory Coleman,
publisher of Memories. Mr. Coleman himself had attempted to
find an outside partner, ideally another large magazine
publisher, to acquire the magazine. "We had a great concept
and things were growing."
   But Mr. Zuckerman was the most realistic suitor. According
to insiders at DCI, Mr. Zuckerman offered to cover the costs
of publishing the October issue, staff salaries, and other
expenses, if Hachette kept the magazine open for two more
weeks, while he worked out financial arrangements. In the
end, Mr. Zuckerman backed out. "It's too tough in this
economy to take on a magazine that doesn't have an automatic
advertising base," he said.
   Hachette's Mr. Guerin said he gave Mr. Zuckerman more than
enough time and information to make a decision. "If we waited
more we would have incurred more losses." Mr. Guerin added,
"if it weren't for Zuckerman, we would have closed Memories
weeks ago."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900905-0131
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900905-0131.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Deep Inside This Big Old Place,
   There's a Mall Trying to Get Out
   ----
   By Gregory L. White
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<LP>
   MOSCOW -- Ever since Stalin ordered it built in 1939, the
U.S.S.R. Exhibition of Economic Achievements has been a
showcase for the supposed triumphs of socialism. But now,
answering the call of capitalism, it's a sort of dotty
Disneyland.
   Its 58 pavilions used to run officially sponsored exhibits
on everything from atomic power to zoology. But government
funding has been cut off, and the 11 million tourists a year
no longer come just to admire the magic of Soviet animal
husbandry or to peer at video recorders, designer shoes and
other goods that aren't for sale in the nation's depleted
stores.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "When there's nothing in the stores, it bothers people to
show things at the exhibition," says Aidar Valiakhmetov. He's
the exhibition's advertising director, a job once known as
head of propaganda.
   Previously, exhibitors weren't allowed to sell their
wares. But today's visitors to the complex -- which is spread
over a 500-acre park in north Moscow -- can, and do, spend
much of their time standing in line for such trinkets as
magnetized ear clips that are said to relieve headaches.
   The consumer-goods pavilion -- fallen prey to the past,
perhaps -- is closed for repairs. But at the agriculture
pavilion, with its huge, stained-glass views of happy,
toiling peasants, Galina Nazarova offers amateur gardeners a
$4-a-bottle miracle liquid that supposedly kills all kinds of
bugs and beetles without harming the environment.
   Next door at the wheat pavilion, the bushels of grain and
loaves of bread on display go unnoticed. In the back room,
however, an exhibit of glass sculptures by a retired
light-bulb maker is well attended, even though the tickets
cost $1.60, six times what visitors pay to get into the
complex itself.
   Capitalism is also tooling along in the machinery
pavilion, which now rents space to anyone who can pay. Around
its dusty satellite models and spacesuits are a video salon,
which shows pirate copies of foreign movies, and a "UFO
shelter," which welcomes visitors who want to chat about
their encounters with extraterrestrials.
   The pavilion's deputy director, 36-year-old engineer
Sergei Kurbatov, is a firm believer in the profit motive. He
even wants to break up the pavilion into a series of
minicompanies, so that unsuccessful ones will fail and not be
carried along by the others. "We are convinced that a person
who works hard should live much better, and a person who
works less should live considerably worse."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900905-0130
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900905-0130.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bank of New England
   To Sell Rhode Island
   Unit for $75 Million
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5
</SO>
<CO>
   NEB RBSA
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKS (BNK)
EASTERN U.S. BANKS (BAE)
</IN>
<LP>
   BOSTON -- Bank of New England Corp. agreed to sell its
Rhode Island subsidiary to Citizens Financial Group, a unit
of the Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, for $75 million,
finishing a program of asset sales that has shrunk the
troubled regional bank by 30% in the past eight months.
   The sale will give the bank holding company $25 million in
profit. The company, which now has $23 billion in assets, is
still working for ways to raise much needed capital,
including a major swap of its debt for equity.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Kent Price, chief financial officer, said the $75 million
is slated for the bank's Massachusetts subsidiary, Bank of
New England N.A., where the combination of low equity and
problem loans, mostly in real estate, has been most serious.
   At the end of the second quarter, the bank's overall
capital ratio, a comparison of equity to assets that
regulators use to measure a bank's health, was 1.64%, well
below the 3% level regulators ordered the bank to meet by May
31, 1990. Healthy banks have levels of 5% or more. The
capital level of the Massachusetts subsidiary, which has been
hovering near 1%, will be raised to about 2% by the infusion
of cash from the Rhode Island deal, according to Mr. Price.
   Bondholders have $706 million in debentures that cost the
bank more than $60 million a year in interest payments. To
induce bondholders to exchange their debt for equity -- a
move that would ease the bank's capital problem -- the bank
needs to offer some cash. With the $75 million from sale of
the Rhode Island subsidiary now spoken for, it is unclear
where that cash could come from. Meanwhile, the bank has an
interest payment of $12.3 million due on Sept. 15.
   The bank, which reported a $1.1 billion loss last year, is
struggling under a huge portfolio of nonperforming assets
that currently total $2.7 billion. Those assets bring no
return while costing the bank about $250 million in interest
payments to customers who deposited that money.
   In the deal announced yesterday , Citizens Financial Group
acquired $900 million in deposits and $600 million in
selected loans from the Rhode Island subsidiary's portfolio.
The Bank of New England will retain about $220 million of the
subsidiary's loans. Mr. Price said some of them were troubled
loans, but he would not specify how many.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900905-0129
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900905-0129.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Economy:
   Manufacturing
   Index Fell to 47%
   During August
   ---
   Purchasing Managers Data's
   Drop Is Second in a Row;
   Construction Posts Gains
   ----
   By Hilary Stout
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
HEAVY CONSTRUCTION; INDUSTRIAL AND COMMERCIAL (CON)
HOME CONSTRUCTION (HOM)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The manufacturing economy deteriorated for
the second consecutive month, according to the National
Association of Purchasing Managers.
   The group's index, which charts orders, production,
employment and other indicators of manufacturing health, fell
to 47% in August, below July's index and its lowest since
January. The association says that when the index drops below
50% it generally indicates that the manufacturing economy is
contracting.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The group surveys purchasing executives in only about 300
companies around the country, but many economists and,
especially the financial markets, watch their index closely
because it is usually the first published report of economic
activity for any month.
   Analysts are particularly hungry for data on the economy's
performance in August, since Iraq's Aug. 2 invasion of Kuwait
sent oil prices soaring and cast new uncertainty on the
nation's economic outlook.
   Manufacturing has been anemic for months. The Federal
Reserve's efforts to fight inflation by maintaining high
interest rates has hurt makers of automobiles and other types
of large, costly machinery and appliances that often are
purchased by borrowing.
   The purchasing managers' index, however, had recently
indicated that manufacturing was picking up from its slump,
by registering above 50% for three consecutive months in the
second quarter. But in July it slipped beneath that
threshold, to 47.4%.
   According to the survey responses, production declined for
the first time since January. New orders were down for the
second straight month, and manufacturing employment declined
for the 18th consecutive month -- at the fastest rate since
January.
   Export orders, however, continued to grow, the report
said, though at the slowest pace since February.
   In a separate economic report yesterday, the Commerce
Department said that construction spending in July increased
0.4%, the first rise in four months. Spending on private
construction grew 0.6%, but the gain was entirely in spending
on business and other nonresidential construction, which
jumped 2.5%. Private residential construction slipped 0.4%.
   Overall construction spending amounted to a $442.20
billion annual rate in July, the department said.
   The numbers in both the purchasing managers and Commerce
Department reports were adjusted for normal seasonal
fluctuations.
                                                                                                       

   Here are the Commerce Department's figures for
construction spending in billions of dollars at seasonally
adjusted annual rates.
                                                                                                       

                                July       June      July
                                1990       1990      1989
                                                                                                       

 Total new construction .....  442.2      440.4      429.0
   Residential ..............  190.5      191.3      196.8
   Nonresidential ...........  107.5      104.9      103.1
   Public ...................  108.6      108.8       95.7
