<HL>
   Martin Marietta
   Faces Intelsat Suit
   On Launch Failure
   ----
   By Mary Lu Carnevale
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   ML
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The International Telecommunications
Satellite Organization (Intelsat) filed a counterclaim
against Martin Marietta Corp. seeking $400 million in damages
for the failed launch of a $150 million communications
satellite.
   The satellite, launched March 14 from a Martin Marietta
Titan III rocket, ended up in a useless orbit after the
system that separated the satellite from the rocket
malfunctioned. Martin Marietta later blamed the trouble on a
"wiring problem, undetected by the processes and test
procedures used in pre-launch checkout."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The original claim by Martin Marietta and the counterclaim
are an important test of satellite launch contracts. Martin
Marietta said in its complaint that if its contract can't be
enforced, the company will have to boost the price of its
Titan III launches, which could make its commercial launch
business uncompetitive.
   Intelsat, an international consortium, argued that Martin
Marietta failed to live up to its contractual obligation and
that slip-ups by the company's management and employees
resulted in the launch failure.
   The claim, filed in federal court in Baltimore Friday,
responds to a complaint filed July 6 by Martin Marietta. The
giant defense contractor, anticipating a lawsuit from
Intelsat, asked the court for a ruling that under the launch
contract, Intelsat assumed the risk of loss of its satellite.
Intelsat, it said, was offered insurance against a launch
failure, but decided against buying it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900905-0027
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900905-0027.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Airlines Seek 5% to 8%
   Fare Rise to Offset Costs
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
</IN>
<LP>
   GENEVA -- Airlines plan to ask their governments for
authority to raise air fares 5% to 8% from Oct. 1 to help
offset higher fuel, insurance and operating costs.
   According to the International Air Transport Association,
which held a three-day conference here last week for some 80
of its 200 member airlines, the carriers agreed to boost
their international tariffs, pending government approvals.
Cargo tariffs will rise 7%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Over the weekend some carriers said they didn't know if
they would follow the pack. Others said they would begin
studying their routes to decide whether to apply a uniform
price increase or to vary it between regions.
   Still other carriers, acting independently, already have
raised their prices to cover higher jet kerosense and
insurance costs related to the Persian Gulf hostilities. Now,
some are separately seeking government permission to add
surcharges on flights to the Middle East. War-risk insurance
premiums on aircraft traveling in the region have soared
since Iraq invaded Kuwait.
   The conference was called because carriers have been
suffering for some time from rising fuel prices, increased
air-traffic control and landing fees and other cost
escalations. The events in the Gulf made the meeting more
timely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
