<HL>
   Business Brief -- Allied-Signal Inc.:
   Garrett Fluid Unit Awarded
   Canadair Systems Contracts
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<CO>
   ALD
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED INDUSTRIAL (IDD)
</IN>
<LP>
   Allied-Signal Inc. said Garrett Fluid Systems, a unit of
its Allied-Signal Aerospace Co. subsidiary, has been awarded
contracts with a potential value of about $60 million to
provide systems for a new 50-passenger Canadair jet.
   A spokesman for Allied-Signal Aerospace said the projected
contract value reflects the company's expectation that
Canadair will build several hundred of this new type of
aircraft.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Garrett Fluid Systems will develop and produce the main
engine-starter system, among other components, for the new
twinengine jetliner, which is scheduled to enter service in
1992.
   Allied-Signal, which is based in Morris Township, N.J.,
has businesses in aerospace, automotive products and
engineered materials. Garrett Fluid Systems, Tempe, Ariz., is
a major supplier of aircraft starters.
</TEXT>
