900905-0006.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bonn Rejects Banks' Bids for `Unity' Bonds
   ----
   By Michael R. Sesit and Terence Roth
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
</IN>
<LP>
   In a move that shocked international bond traders, the
West German government turned down all bids from a group of
banks for 2.5 billion marks ($1.58 billion) of bonds.
   The rejection came after the banks, burned by an
underwriting of similar 8.75%, 10-year bonds on Monday, bid
lower prices for the new offering. Because bond yields move
in the opposite direction of prices, the banks' bids raised
prospective interest rates higher than the West German
Finance Ministry was willing to pay for its debt.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Traders and analysts interpreted the banks' demand for
higher yields as a sign that global capital markets are
becoming saturated by the large volume of West German
government debt needed to finance the unification of East and
West Germany.
   "It also reflected a belief that inflationary pressures
associated with the merger of the two countries are building
and that interest rates are expected to climb further," said
Nicholas P. Sargen, a director of bond-market research at
Salomon Brothers Inc. in New York.
   "The capital market is being burdened like never before,"
said Gert Schmidt, an economist for Industriekreditbank AG in
Dusseldorf. "The question is, how much can it take before
interest rates go higher? It looks as if higher interest
rates are to be the price of unity and the price of not
raising taxes."
   On Monday, a consortium of West German banks and foreign
financial institutions that are licensed to do banking
business in West Germany purchased 2.5 billion marks of
10-year, 8.75%, so-called unity bonds at a discount of 99.20
to yield 8.88%.
   This was to be the first part of a two-part offering, the
second portion being yesterday's tender auction to the same
banking syndicate that underwrote Monday's sale. West German
bankers said yesterday's auction also was supposed to be for
2.5 billion marks.
   But after purchasing the initial 2.5 billion-mark segment
on Monday, the banks discovered yesterday that they couldn't
sell the bonds. "This morning {Tuesday}, there was
disappointment in the market, because it expected a 9%
coupon. The moment the market opened today, the price fell to
98.30," an executive at a big West German bank said. "So we
couldn't sell it {at a profit}. Because the {8.75%} coupon
was so low, it didn't even sell at 99.20, the price at which
we had underwritten it."
   He added that the bank syndicate then offered to buy the
second 2.5 billion-mark portion at 98.10. But "they didn't
accept this offer," he said. Only the Bundesbank, the West
German central bank, tendered on the government's terms,
taking 500 million marks on its books.
   West Germany first began using the two-step method of
selling 10-year government bonds -- an underwriting
syndicate, followed by an auction the next day -- last month,
when it sold six billion marks of unity bonds. Traditionally,
it has sold government debt through an underwriting syndicate
in the same manner as U.S. corporations sell debt to
investors. But traders said the new approach reflected an
evolutionary process that would eventually lead to a
competitive tender system similar to that used by the U.S.
Treasury.
   But traders criticized the two-part system as awkward. A
trader at a West German bank in New York groused, "It is
neither fish nor fowl."
   The problem is that investors who buy the bonds on the
first day can find that the securities have fallen in price
at the time of the second offering on the following day.
"That's what happened in this case; it was clear the issue
was under water," the trader said. "If you are an investor
and subscribe on day one, you are at risk, depending on the
bidding for the second half of the deal. It can go for you or
against you."
   Still, a banker in Frankfurt saw a silver lining in
Tuesday's debacle: "Maybe this was best thing. . . . What we
are moving towards is a full auction, which we do not have."
   Some analysts contended that yesterday's rejected bid
raised the odds that the Bonn government would have to raise
taxes to finance the rebuilding of East Germany, which it
estimates could cost 100 billion marks ($63.37 billion)
annually for the next few years.
   Chancellor Helmut Kohl and Finance Minister Theo Waigel,
who hope to lead the first government elected by a united
Germany since the early 1930s after all-German elections
scheduled for Dec. 2, have firmly ruled out boosting taxes.
The Bonn government has argued that unification can be
financed by existing tax levels -- enhanced by West Germany's
strong growth -- and more borrowing.
   Nonetheless, Chancellor Kohl's opponent in the December
election, Social Democrat Oskar Lafontaine, is insisting that
West Germany has no choice but to raise taxes. And some
private analysts agree.
   "I see tax increases after the elections," said Eckhard
Cornehl, an economist with Bank Julius Baer in Frankfurt. At
the very least, analysts argue that Bonn will have to forgo
corporate tax cuts scheduled for next year.
   Meanwhile, the bond market is feeling the brunt of such
pressures. Ten-year West German government bonds closed to
yield 8.97% yesterday; and at one point in intraday trading,
they were yielding more than 9%. "Clearly the market has
established new higher levels," said John Lipsky, an
international economist at Salomon Brothers in London.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900905-0005
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900905-0005.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   When North Korea Knocks...
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A14
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Yesterday was one of those increasingly frequent occasions
when South Koreans deserved to feel proud. North Korea's
Premier Yon Hyong Muk arrived in the southern capital of
Seoul to meet with South Korea's Premier Kang Young Hoon and
President Roh Tae Woo. There was a brief delay to sort out a
multicar fender-bender in the visitor's motorcade. But then a
dialogue began aimed at reunification of the Korean
peninsula, 40 years after the communist North began the
Korean War with a surprise attack on Seoul. It was a war in
which more than five million Americans served.
   For South Korea, these talks are part of the payoff for
standing up to North Korea's threats and building a
democratic capitalist system that has helped lead Asia's
postwar boom. From the destitute rural economy of the 1950s,
the South has built a world-class trading nation with a per
capita income at least four times that of the misanthropic
North. In 1988, Seoul successfully hosted the summer Olympics
while North Korea's Great Leader Kim Il Sung sulked in
isolated Pyongyang.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   By now, even North Korea's staunchest comrades -- China
and the Soviet Union -- have acknowledged that Kim Il Sung's
Stalin-inspired utopia is going nowhere. The future lies with
the South. China, despite its revived revolutionary rantings
since Tiananmen, has been courting Seoul's business know-how
and investment capital for several years now. In June,
President Gorbachev met with Roh Tae Woo in San Francisco and
announced that Moscow and Seoul would establish diplomatic
ties.
   There is hope in the West that these talks are part of a
sweep toward peaceful reunification that might roughly follow
the script of Germany this past year. The so-called
demilitarized zone that cuts the two Koreas along the 38th
parallel is for Asia at least as potent a symbol of the Cold
War as was the Berlin Wall for Europe. But experience says
that when North Korea knocks at the gates, it's still smart
to beware.
   The North still talks -- and lives -- in terms of
communist revolution. One of the top items on Pyongyang's
agenda is withdrawal from the South of American troops,
currently 38,000-strong, which have helped shore up South
Korea's defense since the 1953 truce. Rational calculation
says that North Korea's leaders would have to be crazy to
start a war now against the South. It is highly doubtful that
either China or the Soviet Union would help the North, and
without their resupplies Pyongyang would be doomed.
Nonetheless, the cost to South Korea and its allies could be
miserably high. And the North's Kim Il Sung during his 42
years of dictatorship has piled up all the credentials of
megalomania. These range from his personality cult and
efforts to install a communist dynasty, to such overseas
projects as bombing a South Korean official delegation in
Rangoon in 1983, and blowing up a South Korean commercial jet
over the Andaman Sea in 1987, killing all 115 people aboard.
   It is alarmingly plausible that with the communist world
breaking up around him, and his own revolution marching down
a dead end, Kim Il Sung might yet try a suicidal last stand.
Certainly there is nothing in his history to suggest that he
will graciously defer to the democrats of Seoul.
   Reunification strictly on South Korea's terms would
satisfy the South's 42 million people and bring vast relief
to the captive 20 million of the North. But there is no
reason for Seoul to rush into any compromise whatsoever with
Pyongyang. Patience has paid off well for Seoul so far.
   The only gifts worth offering to Pyongyang's Premier Yon
this week might be a Korean translation of Adam Smith, and
perhaps about 20 million copies of the June 30, 1987, speech
in which Roh Tae Woo made his winning proposal for South
Korea's transition to democracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900905-0004
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900905-0004.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Who's News:
   American Express
   Names IDS's Golub
   As Vice Chairman
   ----
   By Kevin Goldman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B12
</SO>
<CO>
   AXP WNEWS
</CO>
<IN>
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- American Express Co. named Harvey Golub, the
president and chief executive officer of its IDS Financial
Services Inc. unit, as vice chairman of the parent company.
   In addition, Michael P. Monaco, senior vice president and
acting chief financial officer of American Express, the
travel and financial services giant, was named executive vice
president and chief financial officer.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The 51-year-old Mr. Golub was recruited to IDS from the
consulting firm McKinsey &amp; Co. IDS, a Minneapolis-based
mutual fund, insurance and financial-planning concern, was
purchased by American Express in 1983 for $727 million.
   Mr. Golub also becomes chairman of IDS, a post that has
been vacant, and he will continue as chief executive. The
vice chairman's post at American Express also has been
vacant.
   Jeffrey E. Stiefler, 43, currently IDS's executive vice
president of sales and marketing, was named president of the
unit.
   A spokesman for American Express said yesterday's moves
didn't foreshadow a line of succession to James D. Robinson
III, chairman and chief executive of the parent. Mr.
Robinson, 54, who has been in his position for 13 years, "is
in no hurry to go anywhere," the spokesman said.
   Yesterday's appointments come 16 months after Louis V.
Gerstner resigned as president of American Express to join
RJR Nabisco Inc. Since then, the spokesman said, speculation
about who would succeed Mr. Robinson has increased. The
appointments of Mr. Golub and Mr. Monaco, 42, are part of a
plan "to give the board of directors the maximum number of
choices," the spokesman said.
   "The appointments . . . continue our program to broaden
and develop senior management," Mr. Robinson said in a
statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900905-0003
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900905-0003.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Soviet Farm System Hungers for Reform
   ---
   As Bumper Crops Rot,
   Shoppers and State Despair
   ----
   By Elisabeth Rubinfien
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
09/05/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   MOSCOW -- This summer's Soviet harvest is the biggest ever
-- so large that, even with the usual enormous losses during
handling and processing, it theoretically could meet all the
country's needs. But while millions of tons of grain ripen in
the fields, bread is rationed and hard to find on Moscow's
bakery shelves. And while harvesters gather millions of tons
of vegetables, shoppers find little more than cabbages in the
stores.
   The failure of the Soviet harvesting and distribution
system means Soviet consumers face even more frustration.
Worse yet is the strong possibility that the Soviet Union,
already economically shaky, will have to spend precious hard
currency to import more shiploads of grain.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A tour of the food chain from farm to city grocery
discloses that this year, the Soviet Union's perennial
harvest crisis has been exacerbated by the breakdown of the
old system of Communist Party commands. The much-heralded
market economy -- the advent of which could provide real
motivation -- is barely visible. Meanwhile, any individual
initiative is stifled by bureaucratic lethargy and
indifference.
   At the central office of Shoshensky State Farm, 80 miles
north of Moscow, director Anatoli Poltorikhin describes his
dilemma: he must fulfill production quotas directed from
above while, at the same time, his farm must turn a profit
under new economic policies.
   There isn't enough farm machinery, so Mr. Poltorikhin
relies heavily on horses to work the farm's 15,000 acres. As
he passes one huge machine coughing its way across a golden
field, he warns: "Don't stop the driver to talk. We might
never get the combine started again."
   In past years, farm managers at least could rely on
getting labor reinforcements from local factories during
harvest season. But fledgling economic reforms mean that
industries must become more self-reliant and profitable, so
they have little to gain from volunteering their workers.
   The labor shortage is so great this year that farmers in
several regions have threatened not to provide food to nearby
cities if factory workers weren't sent. Elsewhere, local
governments have declared a state of emergency, giving them
the right to force factories to send workers.
   For years, Moscow has tried to improve farm production.
Recent reforms have enabled more farms to sell part of their
produce directly to consumers at market prices rather than
through the state system. Last year, the government raised
its own purchase prices and started to pay partly in hard
currency for above-quota production.
   The incentives have an edge of desperation to them; the
Soviet Union is running out of hard currency to spend on food
imports. Last year it imported 44 million tons of grain, and
expects to buy at least 20 million tons this year because so
much of the bumper harvest is being lost.
   Mr. Poltorikhin manages 2,700 head of cattle, as well as
450 workers and their families. But all the money his farm
earns goes into an account controlled by bureaucrats in
Moscow. The most he can spend on farm needs at one time
without authority is 25 rubles -- about $40 at the official
exchange rate but only $4 at the more realistic tourist rate.
   Money in the controlled account is supposed to pay for
supplies from the state -- but official channels generally
have little to offer. The press reels off the shortages: As
of mid-August, farmers still lacked spare parts valued at
$480 million, 2,800 grain combines, 2,400 threshers, 17,000
trucks and 360,000 tons of gasoline.
   State farms have offered to pay harvest volunteers, and
television and newspapers have advertised the names of a
dozen farms and vegetable-distribution bases near Moscow that
need labor. But at Lenin State Farm near Moscow, no one seems
eager to deal with volunteers. At the workers' brigade
office, a woman sitting at a desk looks up in irritation as a
would-be apple-picker enters. "I don't know exactly when you
should have been here," she says, "but it's too late now, so
go away."
   The situation is much the same at the next stop along the
food chain: the state-run vegetable-distribution bases
through which almost all fresh produce in the Soviet Union
passes between farm and store. Shura Dyomenaya, a volunteer,
paces angrily in front of the tomato and garlic section of
Dzerzhinsky Base in Moscow. She and 20 other volunteer
workers have waited for an hour, hoping to make the
equivalent of $14 for each ton of tomatoes they sort. The
volunteers have been told they are welcome to work but will
have to come back another time to get paid.
   "It's a society of idiots," Mrs. Dyomenaya says loudly.
"Look, there's lots of work to be done, and it sits there
while they tell us not to work." Some volunteers decide to
take their chances on getting paid eventually and are
assigned to peel garlic. As for the knives that would make
the work easier -- well, there are none.
   Nearby, a train car of watermelons is being unloaded by
the only people who still follow orders: draftees. The army
has sent 46,000 trucks, mobilized air force transport planes
and sent countless soldiers to the fields, according to press
reports.
   Employees at Dzerzhinsky blame the problems on the farms.
"Look at the lousy fruit they sent us," says the director of
cold storage, slapping one pulpy apple down on the browning
one beneath. "They throw in the bad with the good so it all
counts toward their quota."
   But the vegetable bases themselves are widely blamed for
letting produce rot. Truckers allege that some bases won't
let them deliver their loads until the vegetables start to
spoil, so they can buy them at a discount and sell them at
full price.
   The government periodically cracks down. In the early
1980s, the director of Dzerzhinsky Base was executed for
taking bribes. But some base workers and shop managers look
back on those days with nostalgia. "It was run as a
business," recalls Ella Ovakimyan, a base manager. The
executed base director "paid people to make sure he got the
best stuff," she says, "and then he paid his workers extra.
At least it worked."
   Now, truck driver Vyacheslav Grechishnikov is delayed for
an hour at Dzerzhinsky, his load of watermelons sitting in
the sun. "First, the base doesn't have people to unload the
watermelons from the train," he grumbles. "If they have the
people, they don't have the trucks to deliver the fruit. And
if somehow they get the trucks, and we take the stuff to the
store, the shop says they don't need it."
   Thirty minutes later, he pulls up at Store No. 25. The
shop is a large room of empty shelves and cooling units long
since unplugged. A few sacks of green oranges and some
cabbages lie on one shelf, a bin of rotting potatoes near the
checkout.
   Down the back hall in a small office, the driver's
prediction proves true. Lyudmeva Shevlugina, the store
director, turns him and his melons away.
   "We didn't order them, and we don't need them," she says,
crossing her arms. After months of late deliveries from the
base, she got her own truck. In retaliation, the base often
refuses to deliver to her, telling her to use her own truck.
So, she says, her truck picks up melons from a different
source.
   Mrs. Shevlugina starts to cry as she describes the latest
catastrophe. A week earlier, Dzerzhinsky Base sent her three
tons of potatoes in paper sacks. She tears open the paper and
points at the oozing mold.
   "I told them the potatoes are no good, but they say it
isn't their problem," she laments. "And now, I'm supposed to
sell three tons of potatoes, but they're all rotten. How is a
person supposed to work when it's like this?"
</TEXT>
</DOC>
